- Type Design\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sl240\slmult1 Type design is the art of designing \b typefaces.\b0\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sl240\slmult1 - Typeface (Font)\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sl240\slmult1 A typeface is a coordinated set of \b glyphs \b0 designed with stylistic unity. A typeface usually comprises an alphabet of letters, numerals, and punctuation marks; it may also include ideograms and symbols, or consist entirely of them, for example, mathematical or map-making symbols.The term typeface is typically conflated with font, which had distinct meanings before the advent of desktop publishing. These terms are now effectively synonymous when discussing digital typography. One still valid distinction between font and typeface is that a font may designate a specific member of a type family such as roman, bold or italic type, possibly in a particular size, while typeface designates a visual appearance or style, possibly of a related set of fonts. For example, a given typeface such as Arial may include roman, bold, and italic fonts.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sl240\slmult1 - Typography\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sl240\slmult1 Typography is the art and techniques of \b type design\b0 , modifying type \b glyphs\b0 , and arranging type.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sl240\slmult1 - Unicode\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sl240\slmult1 Unicode is an industry standard allowing computers to consistently represent and manipulate text expressed in most of the world's writing systems. Unicode, in intent, encodes the characters of writing systems \emdash  \b graphemes \b0 and grapheme-like units \emdash  rather than the variant \b glyphs \b0 (renderings) for such characters.\par
- related topic: ASCII\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sl240\slmult1 - Vowel\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sl240\slmult1 In \b phonetics\b0 , a vowel is a sound in spoken language that is characterized by an open configuration of the vocal tract so that there is no build-up of air pressure above the glottis. This contrasts with \b consonants\b0 , which are characterized by a constriction or closure at one or more points along the vocal tract. A vowel is also understood to be syllabic: an equivalent open but non-syllabic sound is called a semivowel.\par
In all languages, vowels form the nucleus or peak of syllables, whereas consonants form the onset and (in languages which have them) coda. However, some languages also allow other sounds to form the nucleus of a \b syllable\b0 , such as the syllabic l in the English word table ['te\u618?.bl\u809?] (the stroke under the l indicates that it is syllabic; the dot separates syllables), or the r in the Serbo-Croatian words vrba [vr\u809?.ba] "willow" or vrt "garden".\par
The word vowel comes from the Latin word vocalis, meaning "speaking", because in most languages words and thus speech are not possible without vowels.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sl240\slmult1\tab - related topic: Consonant, Diphthong\par
